subject: yosemitev2:Multi-host CPU info displayed in OCP debug-card.
commitMessage:
yosemitev2:Multi-host CPU info displayed in OCP debug-card.

This implementation is going to display the processor
information in the OCP debug-card.

Tested: information frame value of processor info
displayed in the OCP debug card with multi-host
Yosemitev2 platform.

Signed-off-by: Karthikeyan Pasupathi <p_karthikeya@hcl.com>
Change-Id: Iec29bae79a4c56d92184a69ea187549895f34db9

Patch Set 32: Commit message was updated.
What is this interface?  It isn't documented in phosphor-dbus-interfaces.

This Interface is not documented yet, Still in WIP patch.
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/entity-manager/+/39593

update can be directly initialized ?
uint16_t update = position - 1;
update is uint16_t and result is uint32_t. Please use the correct data type.
This is completely unreadable to me.  Can we get some comments or make a reference to `interface->second` with a saner name?
Please don't use return codes.  Maybe return an empty string on error?
What is with these magic numbers?
Which is i'm using in this function below line No:468, Okay I'll change as per the flow.

Can you just use assignment?  Or store into 'proc' first?  I don't really know what's going on here.

This whole algorithm is very C-style.  Can we make it C++?
Okay, I'll make it in c++.
Let's not use C string parsing functions.
'Byte'?  This looks like you used the wrong naming style to avoid collision with a typename.
I'd like some better documentation on what is going on here.

Is this documented somewhere?  Are you sure 'float' is right?  Should it be 'double'?

Why are we casting to float after the division-by-int?

Please don't use C-style casts.

'freQnz' is an overly cute variable name that doesn't fit the coding conventions.
We're using a stringstream to ... print a floating point?  There should be a more straight-forward way to do that.
What exceptions are even possible here?

In /etc/oemData.json, If any one of the Host details are not populate in oemData.json it leads to runtime error and if particular details are empty or null in oemData.json that leads also an error. Those cases will be handle in that catch block.
Is there a need for these to be a fix-width?  Should we be using 'auto' here?
Yes, for code similarity i'm using those fix-width, as well in ipmiOemSetDimmInfo function.

Are you sure this catch can even do anything?  From `[info]`?  Typically subscript operations are NOT bounds checked but `at` operations are.  Please confirm the bounds checking is even working how you intend here.

I don't really understand why we're switching to a vector here.  Doesn't the IPMI code handle automatic parsing if we pass in a tuple-type of some sort here?  Can't we get the IPMI code to split the request out into mfgId/procIndex/paramSel directly?

The reason for changing the request into vector is already other handlers are follow the same way, So I just want to follow the same format and  also the IPMI code doesn't automatically handle the parsing, So I thought that this is easy way to parse the mfgId/procIndex/paramSel directly.

Ref:
https://github.com/openbmc/fb-ipmi-oem/blob/master/src/oemcommands.cpp#L695
you can use size of mfrId here instead of hardcoding value.

I don't really care for the copying of random bytes without documentation.

Should we just do an assignment or one of the std::algorithms?
initialize variable where it is being used.
This patch has several changes in different handlers. Please split this into multiple patches, so that it will be easier to review.
How about some enumerations instead of magics?
I don't really like this function as it encourages very C-like patterns.  Would be good to queue up a refactoring of this whole file in the future.
Why didn't we put it directly into the `proc` array?

I'd prefer we don't have this return in here.  I don't want to say there is a hard rule that we only return once in a function, but that would certainly be the typical expectation unless there is some if-condition (or else-condition or catch-clause) that makes it clear why we are exiting the function now.
Do we have any desire to log the exception we encountered?
There is no desire log we encountered here.
We should fix up the name on both of these to follow the camelCase pattern used elsewhere.
Did you intentionally add a second S-o-b?  Looks like maybe something changed in your git config.
sorry, it has been added mistakenly.
